Description: Call org_kde_kwin_fake_input::authenticate so KWin dispatches
 button and keyboard events.
 .
 The org_kde_kwin_fake_input protocol requires a client to send an
 ``authenticate(application, reason)`` request before the compositor
 will dispatch any "dangerous" synthetic input -- specifically, button
 presses, keyboard keys, touch events, and axis (scroll) events.
 Pointer motion (including pointer_motion_absolute) is dispatched
 without authentication as a legacy compatibility concession: it is
 what lets kdeconnect's mouse-pad interface show a cursor hint without
 any user-visible permission prompt.
 .
 KRdp 6.6.4's PlasmaScreencastV1Session constructs its ``FakeInput``
 QWaylandClientExtension instance, asserts ``isActive()``, and
 immediately starts feeding input from the RDP client through
 ``pointer_motion_absolute``, ``button``, ``keyboard_key``, and
 ``axis``. Because the ``authenticate`` request is never sent, KWin
 flags the underlying ``FakeInputDevice`` as unauthenticated and
 silently drops button/key/axis events while still honouring pointer
 motion. The visible symptom in mstsc is precisely that: the remote
 cursor follows the user's mouse, but clicks never register and the
 keyboard appears dead.
 .
 This patch sends ``authenticate("KRdp", "Remote Desktop Input")``
 immediately after the FakeInput client extension binds, which makes
 KWin mark our device as authenticated before the first ``button`` or
 ``keyboard_key`` request arrives. The ``application`` string matches
 the ConsoleRDP convention of using "KRdp" for user-visible banners;
 the ``reason`` string is what a future KWin auth-prompt dialog would
 show to the user if KDE ever decides to re-enforce interactive
 authorization.
 .
 Note on the location of the call. The FakeInput constructor runs
 ``initialize()`` then ``Q_ASSERT(isActive())`` to make sure the
 wayland registry contains ``org_kde_kwin_fake_input``; we issue the
 ``authenticate`` request immediately after FakeInput is constructed
 in the Session constructor rather than inside FakeInput itself, so
 the protocol string ("KRdp" / "Remote Desktop Input") stays in one
 place that obviously identifies this server rather than being buried
 in a utility class.
Author: ConsoleRDP <consolerdp@local>
Forwarded: not-yet
Last-Update: 2026-04-30
Bug-KDE: not-yet (intent to file at https://bugs.kde.org/ once tested)

--- a/src/PlasmaScreencastV1Session.cpp
+++ b/src/PlasmaScreencastV1Session.cpp
@@ -163,6 +163,15 @@ PlasmaScreencastV1Session::PlasmaScreencastV1Session()
     , d(std::make_unique<Private>())
 {
     d->remoteInterface = new FakeInput();
+    // org_kde_kwin_fake_input requires an authenticate() request
+    // before KWin will dispatch button, keyboard_key, axis, or touch
+    // events. Pointer motion is exempt (legacy compat), which is why
+    // the mstsc cursor moves while clicks and keystrokes are silently
+    // dropped without this call. See
+    // /usr/share/plasma-wayland-protocols/fake-input.xml for the
+    // protocol description.
+    d->remoteInterface->authenticate(QStringLiteral("KRdp"),
+                                     QStringLiteral("Remote Desktop Input"));
 }
 
 PlasmaScreencastV1Session::~PlasmaScreencastV1Session()
